content.description:
Start up the shared slab then step left to follow the bolts up and left into the stem corner. Awesome rock, reminiscent of Back of the Lake at lake louise. 



Route D. Shares the start with The Granus and Brute Force and Ignorance.

9 bolts

Climb the somewhat dusty slab using hidden holds into a couple of cruxy roof sections, then a not so simple jug haul to finish it off. Great movement.


10 bolts

Route G in topo photo

Is it 10d? Or is it a V2 boulder on a rope? Go up the shared slab and take the jug crack to the roof. Get ready to pull, then fight through the boulder problem. Not a good warmup. The fall from the anchor has been tested as a victory whip.


9 bolts

Route F in the topo

A tribute to the bicycle that is no more. Stellar movement through the bottom section leads to a good rest right before the crux roof, a powerful boulder problem on good holds will take you to the chains. *Jump start* - Stick clip the second bolt and jump to the starting holds (the chicken head and the sloper).



Route R. See the big rock scar to the left of the waterfall? That's the start of the route.

11 bolts

A couple tricky moves get you off the ground. Then fun climbing on good holds leads  you into the crux exiting the last roof. If you manage to find your feet, jugs and a corner crack will lead you to the chains. 



Route A in the topo. Start just to the right of the dead tree.

12 bolts

Start with crimps and a cryptic slab section, then a long pump fest with huge hero jugs most of the way. This might be a good warmup for the harder climbs if you have decent endurance and 5.11 is well within your warmup grades. You can lower to the ground with a 70m rope if the belayer moves a bit up hill.


14 bolts

Route I in the topo

Climbs better than it looks. Stick clip the first or second bolt, then start with a small boulder problem left of the bolt line. Two hard bits further up are separated by a really good shake out. There are multiple beta options for the upper crux, but all seem to be about the same difficulty. 

Don't put an extended draw on the anchor. The final hard move is part of the fun!



Route Q in the topo. Just above the furniture where the approach trail gets to the cliff.

Bolts

Cool sandstone jugs bring you to the break before the slab, which is only slightly easier than the slab on Marky Mark. From the top of the slab, the angle steepens and it’s a hard crux with powerful moves on small holds to the top. 



Route M. To the right of the tall tree

13 Bolts

Sweet sensations and good vibrations all the way. Two main cruxes. Climb decent crimps straight up to the break before the slab, where you might need to find a rest because the slab crux is hard. If you get through, you have some easier ground and a “sit down, take a nap” rest before a crazy crux using some improbable beta high off the ground.

A certain song will definitely help you send: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zjk4CCVxWZM



Route L. Just to the left of the tall tree

13 bolts

Follow the interesting crack feature using the well spaced good holds. Or, do it the hard way if you can’t find the good holds.



To the left of the jumble of boulders at the base of the wall. Route C in the topo

8 bolts

A short, bouldery route with compression and big moves down low, then a very unlikely move that’ll toss you off near the top. Cruxy.

If you want an easier variation, link the bottom of this into the top of Dirty Marmot Party for "Get off my Marmot, 5.10c"



Route B in the topo

10 bolts

Unique climbing for the cove. Start up the shared slab, work your magic on the arete and battle your way into the grey-ness. 



Route E. The line straight up the steepest part of the bulge. 

10 bolts

Powerful moves and small holds. Come on and join the joyride.  

Starts with pretty easy face climbing up to the no-hands rest on the slab, where you can psych yourself up for the powerful crimping you'll have to do in the crux. The crux comes a couple of bolts after the no hands rest, and if you get through there is another good rest before the last boulder and the final moves guarding the chains. 



Route K in topo. To the left of Marky Mark


15 Bolts

This line is a fun 5.7 if you stop at the anchor before the hard part. 



Route F' in the topo. The first anchor on Brute Force and Ignorance

Bolts

Starts to the right of Dixie. Climb up onto the platform and then quest up through the slab/vert section, then through 3 overhanging sections with decent shakes between. Probably a lot easier if you're taller and much more pumpy if you're short. Weird beta, insecure. and fun climbing with slopers, pinches, and some really small footholds.

Clip the anchor with your hands on the ledge above for full value! Don't cheat yourself out of a move.    



Route J in the topo. To the right of Dixie


14 Bolts + anchor

After the fun bouldery section at the bottom, you reach the blue rock and from there it’s smooth sailing on unique features all the way to the chains. 


11 bolts

Route P in the topo. To the left of 3 small trees.

The first half of the route is tricky climbing on hidden holds. Then you have a no-hands rest before a crimpy boulder problem. Traverse left above, then take jugs up to some final tricky mantle moves guarding the chains.


11 bolts

Route N in the topo. Starts just right of the choss ramp.

Great rock and movement on this line. Start with crimpy pulls to reach the slab, which is the first crux of the route. Then launch into the long hard journey to the top, which is protected by a dynamic boulder problem.


11 bolts

Route H in the topo

The more sustained version of Prancing. A really interesting sequence on crimps leads you through the tough part, then it’s easier moves on sweet rock to the top.


11 bolts

Route O in the topo. Between Prancing and Pelvic Sorcery

A new area bolted in 2020-2021, has a wide selection of grades from 5.9 to 5.13. The style is mostly slabby to slightly overhanging technical and crimpy routes, but there are a few steeper lines with plenty of jugs. All routes are climbable with a 70m rope, but tie a knot in the end of your rope for the longer routes for safety. Routes are designed to be stick clipped. Wearing a helmet is a good idea since this is a newer area, and it is Moose after all.

At the peak of summer, the wall gets about 1 hour of sun in the late afternoon. All other times of year it's sending temps (ie, cold).
